Description: Provides data-processing, modelling, resampling, and visualization
    tools used to study how the progressive accumulation of trials affects
    effect estimates, uncertainty, variance components, standardized effect
    sizes, and test statistics in repeated-measures experiments. The project
    focuses on three classical experimental psychology paradigms: the Simon
    task, the Spatial Numerical Association of Response Codes (SNARC) task,
    and task switching. Gaussian and generalized mixed-effects models are used
    to distinguish gains in precision from systematic changes in the effect or
    its variance components across the course of an experiment.
